Preheat your #oven{} to 240°C/220°C fan/gas mark 9. Chop the @sweet potato{2} into 1cm chunks (no need to peel).

Pop the sweet potato onto a large #baking tray{}. Drizzle with @oil{}, season with @salt{} and @pepper{}, then toss to coat. Spread out in a single layer.

> TIP: Use two baking trays if necessary.

When the oven is hot, roast on the top shelf until golden, ~{18-20%minutes}. Turn halfway through.

Meanwhile, drain and rinse the @cannellini beans{1%carton} in a #sieve{}. Grate the @mature cheddar cheese{40%grams}.

Peel and grate the @garlic clove{3}(peeled and grated) (or use a #garlic press{}).

Halve the @ciabatta{1} and lay onto a medium baking tray, cut-side up. Spread over half the garlic, drizzle with @oil{} and season with @salt{}. Set aside.

Heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a large #saucepan{} on medium-high heat.

Once hot, add the @diced chorizo{90%grams} and fry until starting to brown, ~{3-4%minutes}. Stir in the @Cajun spice mix{1%sachet} (add less if you'd prefer things milder) and remaining garlic. Stir-fry until fragrant, ~{30%seconds}.

Add the cannellini beans, @tomato passata{1%carton}, @vegetable stock paste{10%grams}, @creme fraiche{75%grams}, @sugar{1%tsp} and @water{75%ml} for the stew (see pantry for both amounts).

Stir to combine, bring to the boil, then lower the heat and simmer until slightly reduced, ~{5-6%minutes}.

Meanwhile, bake the garlic bread on the middle shelf of your oven until golden, ~{5-6%minutes}.

When ready, cut the garlic bread diagonally into triangles.

Once the stew has slightly reduced, add the @baby spinach{100%grams} and roasted sweet potato. Stir to combine and simmer until piping hot, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Stir in the @butter{20%grams} until melted.

Taste and season with @salt{} and @pepper{} if needed. Add a splash of @water{} if it's a little too thick.

Share the Cajun chorizo and sweet potato stew between your #bowls{}. Sprinkle over the cheese to finish.

Serve the garlic bread alongside. Enjoy!